{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"alias":"vocal-dip-robin","description":"## Summary\n`tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_transition_open_children.py::test_guard_counts_only_direct_children_not_unrelated`\nis FLAKY in CI: it passes locally and on re-run, but intermittently fails with a git-state race\nin its temporary rebar-store fixture. Observed repeatedly while landing epic sure-foyer-aroma's\n13-change Gerrit stack — different changes' CI runs failed on this one test, each cleared by a\n`recheck`, and it passes deterministically when run locally in isolation.\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n1. Push a stack of changes to Gerrit (or otherwise trigger the full default CI suite repeatedly).\n2. Observe that on some runs this single test fails during its temp-store setup, while 4500+ other\n   tests pass; a `recheck` (same patchset, no code change) then passes.\nTwo distinct failure signatures observed (both git races in the fixture's temp repo):\n- Run 28825842708 (change 325, ps2): `rebar._errors.RebarError: rebar transition failed (exit 2):\n  Error: git operation failed: fatal: could not parse HEAD`\n- Run 28828139721 (change 339): `rebar._errors.RebarError: rebar create failed (exit 1):\n  Error: git commit failed while holding lock`\n\n## Expected vs Actual\n- **Expected:** the test is deterministic — it passes on every run given identical code (it passes\n  locally 100% of the time and on CI rechecks).\n- **Actual:** it fails intermittently in CI (~1 in N runs) with a git error (`could not parse HEAD`\n  / `git commit failed while holding lock`) originating in the temp rebar-store setup, not in the\n  behavior under test (the direct-children guard count). The failure is environment/timing-driven.\n\n## Likely Root Cause (hypothesis — confirm before fixing)\nThe test's fixture builds a temp rebar store and performs `create`/`transition` against it. The two\nsignatures suggest either (a) an operation running before the store's git HEAD/initial commit is\nfully established (`could not parse HEAD`), or (b) `index.lock` contention — a prior git op's lock\nnot yet released, or concurrent access under xdist/parallel CI. Investigate the fixture's\nstore-init ordering and any lock-release/retry gap in the `git commit`/`create` path used under\ntest. This is a TEST/fixture-reliability bug, not a defect in the transition-guard behavior itself.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Root cause of the intermittent git race in the fixture is identified (HEAD-not-ready vs\n      index.lock contention) and documented.\n- [ ] The fixture (or the store-init/commit path it exercises) is made deterministic — e.g. ensure\n      the initial commit/HEAD exists before ops, and/or the lock acquisition retries/serializes —\n      so the test cannot fail on this race.\n- [ ] The test passes reliably under repeated/parallel CI runs (no `recheck`-only greens); ideally\n      add a stress/repeat guard or a regression note so the flake does not silently return.","id":"edf7-946e-84be-48b3","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"Flaky test_guard_counts_only_direct_children_not_unrelated: intermittent git-race (could not parse HEAD / index.lock) in temp-store fixture"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783381198348418001,"uuid":"0de72c63-fec0-4614-944a-902d2287f99b"}